@endnode

@node pascal "Source code"
	Source code can be supplied together with the package, but needn't.
	Feel free to use it as a base for improvements.
	The following hints may be useful:

	PCQ uses typed constants, i. e. initialized variables (borrowed
	from TurboPascal on other platforms); I fear that other compilers
	don't understand this syntax. At the other hand, PCQ refuses to
	read constant arrays in another way.

	AllocString is a special function of PCQ. Leaving it out would lead
	to a crash, so don't be surprised...
	GetParam is also PCQ-specific syntax, e. g. in Turbo it is ParamStr.

	Lnginit: the procedure to read the cat file. If international usage
	isn't desired, it can be replaced by a constant definition.

	Getyear reads the year eather from the command line or asks for it.

	Rescalc is the core algorithm. I don't actually know whether it has
	been written by a Mr. Hartmann or by Carl Friedrich Gauss. But there
	is no copyright on it, so don't think twice...

	Typeout: just that

	Orgfile: reads a template and writes it into RAM-Disk with the real
	appointments. Note that an uppercase N is detected as part of the
	marker EVNT in the organiser file, so it's bad luck if one of the
	holidays begins with N in your language.

	Compiled with PCQ, I get a file length of approx. 9 kB, 1˝ kB can be
	saved by leaving out either the user interface or the interface to
	@{"Organiser" link orga}. I assume that a commercial compiler could
	produce a shorter executable file.
@endnode

