@node PCQ "PCQ"
	An American Pascal compiler, released as Freeware. The author admits
	that PCQ can't compete with C compilers for the Amiga, but I don't
	like C as a language, and I don't code enough for buying MaxonPascal.
@endnode

@node EdWord "EdWord"
	A Shareware editor that is primarily designed for coding. (Bracket
	matching, keywordfiles, access to external compilers etc.) It also
	loads executable files or data in any format without changes.
	I used it both for coding and for analyzing the @{"Organiser" link orga} format.
	Don't get it if you dislike 8*8 fixed fonts.
@endnode

@node options "Command line options"
	East runs from the command line. Workbench usage requires the CLI
	parameter in the tool types.
	The following parameters are supported:

	? to show usage (must be first, others ignored)

	c (lowercase, must be first) as a switch to show also Corpus Christi,
	what only seems necessar in catholic regions. Otherwise, only Good
	Friday, Easter, Ascension Day and Whitsun will be shown.

	1997, or what ever you type as a year. Abbreviations are invalid.
	If the year is missing, you are asked for it.
@endnode

@node system "Requirements"
	As far I know, there are no restrictions about Kickstart and
	Workbench version. Up to now, I only tested on an A 600.

	Please note that a catalog file must be located in the same
	directory as the program file. @{"LOCALE:" link locale} is not checked.
@endnode

@node locale "Localization of East"
	East looks for a catalog file in the current directory. It doesn't
	meet the template of WB 2.1, it simply concats the lines as shown:

  1-4 th of March etc. (Sorry, st-nd-rd are not supported)
  5-9 Good Friday etc. (The 5 major holidays)      
   10 Calendar from 1978 (Orgfiles only within the range of Amiga Calendar)
   11 From 1900 to ... (I didn't provide more validity than required)
   12 @{"No correct template ... " link template}
   13 Bye! (Message after running correctly)
   14 version number, also dummy for command line
   15 Can't open RAM-Disk ... (file already in usage? write protected?)
   16 Please enter year (four digits)!
   17 Usage:
18-19 Filenames of the templates without and with Corpus Christi


	If you want to translate the cat file, please remind that the
	lines shouldn't be confused. It seems the best way to load an
	existing version and translate it line by line.
@endnode

@node template "Localization of East"
	East looks for a template file in the current directory. It is
	nothing else than an @{"Organiser" link orga} appointment file which
	contains all required holidays. East recalculates the dates
	depending from the year.
	Important note: don't use uppercase N in a template file!
@endnode

@node what "What is East?"
	The holidays in spring (Good Friday, Easter, Ascension Day, Whitsun
	and (frequently) Corpus Christi) are celebrated at appointments that
	change with the year. To be precise, Easter Sunday is the sunday
	after the first time moon is full in spring.
	A program that calculates Easter Sunday does already exist ( and I
	used it for testing correctness - the results are equal, despite both
	programs are independent from each other).
	May it just be a question of convenience, it seemed me boring to cal-
	culate the other holidays by hand and enter them, one by one, in an
	@{"Organiser" link orga} file. So I wrote East.
	East outputs the appointments of all these holidays both on the
	screen and into an appointment file to be loaded with @{"Organiser" link orga}.
	Don't forget that orgfiles can be concatenated by loading the second
	one, while the SHIFT key is pressed.
@endnode

@node orga "Organiser"
	Digita Organiser is (c) Digita International Limited.
	East 1.0 and its doc file refer to version 1.1.
	I HOPE that later versions will also read the files produced by East,
	but I don't assume that they create the required templates.
@endnode

